      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented simulation setup review and independent verification of boundary condition inputs.",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup reviewed by a second engineer independent of the analyst. Boundary condition inputs verified against experimental protocol documentation. Mesh topology and solver settings reviewed against laboratory standard operating procedure SOP-CFD-002. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Governing equations and constitutive models appropriate for the physics of interest, with documented justification.",
      "rationale": "Incompressible Reynolds-averaged Navier-Stokes with SST k-ω turbulence closure selected based on published benchmark comparisons for rotating blood pump flows. Non-Newtonian viscosity modeled via Carreau-Yasuda constitutive relation. Power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen et al.) applied with coefficients validated for bovine blood. Model form appropriateness documented in modeling report MR-2024-07. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material properties and boundary condition inputs traceable to documented sources with uncertainty characterization.",
      "rationale": "Blood viscosity, density, and hemolysis model coefficients sourced from peer-reviewed literature with documented uncertainty ranges. Pump geometry dimensions obtained from manufacturer-supplied CAD with dimensional inspection report. Inlet velocity profiles derived from Womersley flow assumption validated against PIV measurements. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples used in validation are representative of the device population relevant to the COU.",
      "rationale": "Experimental hemolysis data collected using three independently fabricated FDA generic pump specimens machined to nominal dimensions. Sample-to-sample variability in hemolysis index < 6%, consistent with manufacturing tolerance analysis. Specimens representative of the production device population. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Demonstration that input parameters used in validation experiments are equivalent to those encountered in the COU clinical environment.",
      "rationale": "The assessment team determined that this factor does not apply to the present COU because the study is a purely computational sensitivity analysis with no physical test article differing from the validation specimen. Clinical use parameters (blood temperature, hematocrit variability, anticoagulant effects) were not systematically compared against validation inputs. This factor was therefore left unassessed rather than formally scoped out, on the informal basis that the computational nature of the COU renders it irrelevant — a judgment that was not subjected to the structured applicability review required under ASME V&V 40 Table 5-1 for MRL 3."
    }
